{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5135279d-007a-4fc9-946e-2899eb8b440c","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes and `createdump` isn't available, you have two main options:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates `.ips` crash reports in:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   These contain the stack trace, signal info, and loaded images. Open them with Console.app or any text editor.\n\n2. **Core dumps** — macOS can generate core dumps, but they're disabled by default. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file typically lands in `/cores/core.<pid>`. You can inspect it with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n**Tip:** The `.ips` crash report is usually the quickest path — it's generated automatically with no setup required.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bfbfa1b4-67e5-42bd-9795-d32535f58a59","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a knowledge question, not a code task. I can answer directly.","outputTokens":289,"requestId":"AC09:2E3AFD:13CBEE7:163F782:6A067164"},"id":"13ec8794-8d34-4dc4-820a-5038c0bd28e0","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:05:47.701Z","parentId":"3d7e7a01-df8e-4818-9d66-4697b3eb29eb"}
